    <div class="reply">
      <a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='#comment-15945' data-commentid="15945" data-postid="1018" data-belowelement="comment-15945" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to Susan" aria-label='Reply to Susan'>Reply</a>    </div>
  </li><!-- #comment-## -->
  <li id="comment-15946" class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn">Anonymous</cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2009/02/a-first-rate-mess/#comment-15946"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2009-03-04T04:58:00-05:00">Wednesday, March 4, 2009 at 4:58 am</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>I live in Kodiak, Alaska, after many years in Northern California where a December meal of Dungeness crab marked the beginning of the Christmas season. We live-backed them on a redwood fence in the backyard and served them on a tablecloth on the floor accompanied by melted garlic butter, sourdough French bread and salad. I had a friend who made a remarkable tomato crab fennel soup. King crab has nowhere near the refined taste and texture of Dungeness. I am so inspired to make your scallop soup with Alaska scallops!</p>
    </div>

    <div class="reply">
      <a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='#comment-15946' data-commentid="15946" data-postid="1018" data-belowelement="comment-15946" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to Anonymous" aria-label='Reply to Anonymous'>Reply</a>    </div>
